Here are the MSTest patterns for each scenario:

**1. Windows-only (platform filter):**
```csharp
[TestMethod]
[OSCondition(OperatingSystems.Windows)] // custom attribute, or:
public void RegistryTest()
{
    if (!RuntimeInformation.IsOSPlatform(OSPlatform.Windows))
        Assert.Inconclusive("Windows only");
    // test logic
}
```

**2. Skip in CI (conditional skip):**
```csharp
[TestMethod]
[TestCategory("RequiresGPU")]
public void GpuTest() { /* ... */ }

// Then exclude in CI: dotnet test --filter "TestCategory!=RequiresGPU"
// Or check at runtime:
if (Environment.GetEnvironmentVariable("CI") == "true")
    Assert.Inconclusive("Skipped in CI — requires local GPU");
```

**3. Flaky external API (retry with `[TestMethod]` timeout + defensive code):**
```csharp
[TestMethod]
[Timeout(10000)] // fail fast if API hangs
[RetryAttribute(3)] // MSTest 3.x+ built-in retry (or use a custom IRetryAnalyzer)
public void WeatherApiTest()
{
    try {
        var result = CallWeatherApi();
        Assert.IsNotNull(result);
    } catch (HttpRequestException) {
        Assert.Inconclusive("Weather API unavailable");
    }
}
```

> **Note:** `[Retry(n)]` was added in **MSTest v3.8+**. For older versions, implement `IRetryAnalyzerAttribute`.

**4. Cleanup even on failure — use `[TestCleanup]` or `try/finally`:**
```csharp
private string? _tempFile;

[TestInitialize]
public void Setup() =>
    _tempFile = Path.GetTempFileName();

[TestCleanup] // runs even if the test throws
public void Cleanup()
{
    if (_tempFile != null && File.Exists(_tempFile))
        File.Delete(_tempFile);
}

[TestMethod]
public void FileProcessingTest()
{
    File.WriteAllText(_tempFile!, "data");
    // test logic — if this throws, Cleanup still runs
}
```

**Summary table:**

| Scenario | Pattern |
|---|---|
| OS-specific | `Assert.Inconclusive()` guard or custom condition attribute |
| Skip in CI | `[TestCategory]` + `--filter`, or env-var check |
| Flaky API | `[Retry(3)]` (v3.8+) + `[Timeout]` + `Assert.Inconclusive` fallback |
| Cleanup | `[TestCleanup]` — always runs, even on failure |
